  "doc_id": "24821",
  "text": "Our results make a strong case that GRK1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice have a specific defect in the inactivation of cone phototransduction, as follows. First, besides its expression in mammalian rods, GRK1 has only been found to be present in cones ; consistent with this general finding, the antisense probe generates no signal in the inner nuclear layer (Fig. 1) , as would be expected, for example, were GRK1 present in cone ON bipolars and playing a role in their mGluR6 cascade [CITATION_1] . Thus, the cone b-wave recoveries of the GRK1 Ϫ/Ϫ mutants are not retarded because of a defect in the G-protein signaling cascade of the cone ON bipolars, but rather these slowed recoveries point to a defect in the cone photoreceptors that drive them. Second, the greatly slowed recoveries of the a-wave component recorded under cone isolation conditions provide specific functional evidence for a defect in the inactivation of cone transduction. The evidence is compelling because the ERG component isolated in Figure 6 (thickened portion of traces) is the murine cone a-wave, i.e., represents the suppression of the circulating current of the cones. Specifically, as presented previously [CITATION_2] , this component has the sign, magnitude, and activation kinetics expected from human ERG studies [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and from microelectrode recordings from single mammalian cones [CITATION_6] for generation in the suppression of cone circulating current. Thus, the greatly slowed recovery of the cone-isolated a-wave in GRK1 Ϫ/Ϫ mutants (Figs. 6, 7B) shows that the circulating currents of the cones of the mutant mice recover much more slowly from the conditioning flash than do the cone circulating currents of WT mice or those of mice lacking arrestin, which is necessary for normal rod inactivation [CITATION_7] (Fig. 3A, c, f ) .",
